Social Analytics and Strategic Intelligence

Session 1: Explore and Query

Lets get the data we produced in Pytho into R. Here, ByYear_stats:

rm(list = ls())
denguelink='https://github.com/SocialAnalytics-StrategicIntelligence/OrganizeExploreAndQuery/raw/main/dataFiles/ByYear_stats.pkl'

# opening the pickle data:

library(reticulate)
# py_install("pandas") # install pandas for R environment
pd <- import("pandas")
dengueStats <- pd$read_pickle(denguelink)

# you goy the right data type!
str(dengueStats) 
## 'data.frame':    59 obs. of  5 variables:
##  $ ano        : num  2000 2001 2001 2002 2002 ...
##  $ enfermedad : Ord.factor w/ 3 levels "SIN_SEALES"<..: 1 1 3 1 2 3 1 3 1 3 ...
##  $ edad_mean  : num  29.5 30.6 31.6 27 12 ...
##  $ edad_median: num  27 28 28 24 12 19 27 30 26 19 ...
##  $ case_sum   : num  4324 15851 241 6278 1 ...
##  - attr(*, "pandas.index")=RangeIndex(start=0, stop=59, step=1)

Are the symptoms distributed fairly the same accross ages?

  • Using the mean:
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data=dengueStats,aes(x=ano,y=edad_mean)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(aes(color=enfermedad))

  • Using the median:
ggplot(data=dengueStats,aes(x=ano,y=edad_median)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(aes(color=enfermedad))

How is the collection of information?

  • Basic plot
ggplot(data=dengueStats,aes(x=ano,y=case_sum)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(aes(color=enfermedad))

  • Semi-log plot
ggplot(data=dengueStats,aes(x=ano,y=case_sum)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(aes(color=enfermedad)) + scale_y_log10(labels = scales::comma)

Lets bring the same data in long format (ByYear_LongStats):

denguelink2='https://github.com/SocialAnalytics-StrategicIntelligence/OrganizeExploreAndQuery/raw/main/dataFiles/ByYear_LongStats.pkl'

dengueLongStats <- pd$read_pickle(denguelink2)


str(dengueLongStats) 
## 'data.frame':    177 obs. of  4 variables:
##  $ ano       : num  2000 2000 2000 2001 2001 ...
##  $ enfermedad: Ord.factor w/ 3 levels "SIN_SEALES"<..: 1 1 1 1 1 1 3 3 3 1 ...
##  $ statsName : chr  "edad_mean" "edad_median" "case_sum" "edad_mean" ...
##  $ statsValue: num  29.5 27 4324 30.6 28 ...
##  - attr(*, "pandas.index")=RangeIndex(start=0, stop=177, step=1)

Facets will help create complex plots in an easy way:

  • All the stats by year (smooth - semilog):
facets= ggplot(data=dengueLongStats,
               aes(x=ano,y=statsValue,color=enfermedad)) + theme_light() +
        facet_grid(statsName~.,scales = 'free_y') + 
    scale_y_log10(labels=scales::comma) 
facets +    geom_smooth() 

facets +
    geom_line()

The data worst_ProvYear_alarma_Frequency tell us the frequency of the worst province by region by year:

denguelink3='https://github.com/SocialAnalytics-StrategicIntelligence/OrganizeExploreAndQuery/raw/main/dataFiles/worst_ProvYear_alarma_Frequency.csv'

dengueProvWorst <- read.csv(denguelink3)


str(dengueProvWorst) 
## 'data.frame':    43 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ departamento: chr  "AMAZONAS" "AMAZONAS" "ANCASH" "ANCASH" ...
##  $ provincia   : chr  "BAGUA" "UTCUBAMBA" "CASMA" "SANTA" ...
##  $ case        : int  6 6 5 3 1 7 1 1 10 2 ...

For instance, LORETO has data for 14 years:

dengueProvWorst[dengueProvWorst$departamento=='LORETO',]
##    departamento     provincia case
## 28       LORETO ALTO AMAZONAS    1
## 29       LORETO        MAYNAS   13

In one year, ALTO AMAZONAS was the wors case of people with alarm situation; while MAYNAS had that position for 13 years.

We could see distribution of the worst provinces:

baseHeat  = ggplot(dengueProvWorst, aes(x = reorder(departamento,case), y = reorder(provincia,case), fill=case)) + theme_classic()
heatDefault = baseHeat +  geom_tile() #here

heatBetter=heatDefault +scale_fill_gradient(low = 'yellow',high = 'black')
heatBetter + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60,vjust = 1,hjust = 1),
                   axis.text.y = element_text(size=4)) +
                   geom_text(aes(label=ifelse(case>=10,case,"")),
                             size=6,fontface='bold', color='white')

Where and when?

# default 

baseHeat  = ggplot(dengueYearPlace, aes(x = as.factor(ano),
                                       y =reorder(departamento,
                                                  rateAlarma), 
                                       fill=rateAlarma.cut)) + theme_classic()
heatDefault = baseHeat +  geom_tile(show.legend = T) #here

heatBetter=heatDefault +scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Reds")
